<h2>What this is</h2>
<p>You will pick one of <strong>8 water-rights disputes</strong>. Within that case, you'll pick one <strong>stakeholder perspective</strong> (each case has 6–7 stakeholder options — farmer, government, industry, downstream community, NGO, etc.). You then produce a <strong>Stakeholders Map</strong> (a visual representation of who's involved, what they want, how they relate) plus a <strong>Position Paper</strong> (2 pages or 4-min video) advocating for your chosen stakeholder's position — <em>not your own default view</em>.</p>
<p>The defense is a <strong>multi-stakeholder Roundtable</strong> — peers representing competing stakeholders in the same case actively argue, propose, refuse, seek compromise. This is the fourth defense in the year-long arc and the first one with a real negotiation format (not Q&amp;A). The Roundtable does not need to reach consensus; real disputes often don't. What matters is whether you can hold your stakeholder's position under pressure <em>while</em> engaging the legitimate concerns of competing stakeholders.</p>

