<h2>The Stakeholders Map — 7-field template</h2>
<p>Build a map of ≥5 distinct, <strong>specific</strong> stakeholders in your chosen case. For each, fill all 7 fields:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Stakeholder Name</strong> — be specific. "Tamil Nadu Cauvery delta rice farmers (5th-generation, Thanjavur)" not "farmers."</li>
  <li><strong>Who They Are</strong> — 1–2 sentences identifying the specific group.</li>
  <li><strong>What They Want</strong> — primary interest, in their framing.</li>
  <li><strong>Evidence They Cite</strong> — what supports their position? Data, history, lived experience, legal documents.</li>
  <li><strong>Position</strong> — what specifically should happen?</li>
  <li><strong>Power</strong> — how much influence do they have? How do they exercise it?</li>
  <li><strong>Allies + Opponents</strong> — who do they align with? Against?</li>
</ol>
<p>Plus a 1-page narrative walking the reader through the map's key tensions, alliances, and contested claims.</p>

<h2>The Position Paper — 4-part structure</h2>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Opening</strong> (~150 words) — establish who's speaking + what's at stake from this stakeholder's view. Use their voice from word 1. ("My grandfather walked off the troopship in Sydney in 1932…" not "A farmer would argue…")</li>
  <li><strong>Core argument</strong> (~500–700 words) — argue this stakeholder's position using evidence <em>they</em> would cite. Specific data, events, harms or benefits as the stakeholder experiences them.</li>
  <li><strong>Acknowledge competing concerns</strong> (~150–200 words) — real stakeholders acknowledge other parties' concerns. Acknowledge ≥1 legitimate competing concern <em>without conceding</em> your position. Stating the competing concern fairly is the move.</li>
  <li><strong>Negotiation opening</strong> (~100 words) — what trade or compromise might this stakeholder accept? What would they <em>never</em> accept? Real stakeholders signal both willingness and boundaries.</li>
</ol>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">Critical rule — voice-match</div>
  <p>The Position Paper is <strong>not your personal opinion in a different name</strong>. If your paper reads the same regardless of which stakeholder you chose, perspective-taking work hasn't happened. The voice-match move is the entire T/T centerpiece of the assessment.</p>
</div>

<h2>Required components</h2>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Stakeholders Map</strong> (visual + 1-page narrative)</li>
  <li><strong>Position Paper</strong> (2 pages written OR 4-min captioned video)</li>
  <li><strong>AI Documentation Template</strong> — <em>required</em>, not optional. Documents your AI use (Hydrologist for case hydrology; Stakeholder Voice for perspective-taking; any other AI). Section A students document the Boodle Build process separately — what design choices, which felt right, what the bot got wrong when peer-tested.</li>
  <li><strong>Stakeholder Roundtable participation</strong> — 2-min opening statement + ≥3 substantive responses to competing stakeholders + at least 1 negotiation move (proposing trade, conceding a point, asking substantive clarifying question).</li>
</ol>

<h2>What you'll be scored on</h2>
<p>U5 introduces <strong>perspective-taking as the year's T/T centerpiece</strong>. K/U covers water-systems + water-rights knowledge. T/T covers whether you genuinely argued from the stakeholder's perspective (not your own). C covers clarity + Roundtable engagement + voice-match across formats.</p>
<p><strong>Grade weighting</strong>: Stakeholders Map + Position Paper 65% · Stakeholder Roundtable 20% · Formative work (Blocks 1–4 activities, OPVL practice, stakeholder mapping, peer feedback) 15%.</p>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">Four scoring gates worth naming up front</div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Voice-match is a T/T gate.</strong> If your Position Paper reads as your own view in slightly different words (same arguments + evidence you'd personally cite), T/T caps at 3–4. The whole assessment is built around perspective-taking; if you didn't take the perspective, T/T reflects that.</li>
    <li><strong>Stakeholder specificity is a K/U gate.</strong> If your Stakeholders Map names generic groups ("farmers," "government," "environmentalists") instead of specific identifiable stakeholders, K/U caps at 5–6.</li>
    <li><strong>AI Documentation is a K/U gate.</strong> Same as prior units. If AI used and Template missing or trivial, K/U caps at 3–4. Section A's Boodle Build documentation is required.</li>
    <li><strong>Negotiation move is a C signal.</strong> Strong Paper + mere restatement in Roundtable (no real negotiation move) caps C at 5–6. The Roundtable is negotiation, not Q&amp;A.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<h2>Rubric — K/U / T/T / C across 4 bands</h2>

<h3>K/U — Knowledge &amp; Understanding</h3>
<p><em>The student recalls facts, terms and definitions while also explaining concepts, ideas, processes, themes. The student performs skills related to their studies.</em></p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>7–8 (Exemplary):</strong> Exemplary knowledge of hydrology + water-rights frameworks. Map identifies ≥5 distinct, specific stakeholders. Water cycle, watershed, quality concepts correctly applied. Vocabulary (riparian, prior appropriation, public trust, conjunctive use) precise. Hydrology of case correct.</li>
  <li><strong>5–6 (Proficient):</strong> Map identifies 5+ stakeholders, mostly specific. Hydrologic concepts mostly correct. Vocabulary mostly accurate.</li>
  <li><strong>3–4 (Developing):</strong> Stakeholders generic. Hydrology with conceptual errors. Vocabulary inconsistent.</li>
  <li><strong>1–2 (Limited):</strong> Stakeholders missing or all generic. Hydrology absent. Vocabulary missing.</li>
</ul>

<h3>T/T — Thinking &amp; Transfer</h3>
<p><em>The student plans for learning by formulating questions, generating ideas, researching. The student thinks critically. The student applies knowledge to unfamiliar contexts.</em></p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>7–8 (Exemplary):</strong> Highly effective perspective-taking. Position Paper argues from stakeholder's view using THEIR evidence, not student's own. Voice matches stakeholder. Competing concerns acknowledged honestly. Specific negotiation move proposed. Map shows power, alliances, evidence-gaps. OPVL rigorous on politically diverse sources. AI-source limitations specific.</li>
  <li><strong>5–6 (Proficient):</strong> Proficient perspective-taking. Paper mostly stays in voice; appropriate evidence but some default-view bleed. Competing concerns acknowledged. Map shows correct relationships.</li>
  <li><strong>3–4 (Developing):</strong> Paper reads as student's own view in different name — argues from personal preference, not stakeholder's framing. Map identifies but doesn't show dynamics.</li>
  <li><strong>1–2 (Limited):</strong> No real attempt to argue from stakeholder view — either student's own position or caricature. No competing concerns. Map missing.</li>
</ul>

<h3>C — Communication</h3>
<p><em>The student expresses and organizes ideas in multiple forms. The student adapts communication to different audiences. The student uses conventions, terminology and vocabulary relevant to the discipline.</em></p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>7–8 (Exemplary):</strong> Map visually clear; narrative confident. Position Paper voice genuinely matches stakeholder. Vocabulary precise. Citations clean. Roundtable: opens crisply, engages substantively, makes clear negotiation move. AI Doc clearly written.</li>
  <li><strong>5–6 (Proficient):</strong> Map mostly clear with logical narrative. Paper voice mostly matches; minor slips. Vocabulary precise most of time. Roundtable solid; some responses lack depth.</li>
  <li><strong>3–4 (Developing):</strong> Map partially clear; narrative rough. Paper voice inconsistent. Vocabulary errors. Roundtable restates opening; minimal engagement.</li>
  <li><strong>1–2 (Limited):</strong> Map unclear or missing narrative. Paper voice absent. Beginner vocabulary. Roundtable minimal.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Reporting format.</strong> Each strand is reported as its own band score (e.g., "K/U 7, T/T 6, C 7"). Not summed. The triplet IS the grade.</p>

<h2>AI Documentation</h2>
<p>Required regardless of which arm you're in. If you use the <a href="/ai-partners/the-hydrologist/">Hydrologist</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/stakeholder-voice/">Stakeholder Voice</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/the-source-evaluator/">Source Evaluator</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/the-skeptic/">Skeptic</a>, or any other AI tool, the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a> is required. <strong>Section A</strong> students additionally document the Boodle Build process: what design choices you made when constructing your stakeholder's bot, which iterations felt authentic, which the bot got wrong when peer-tested. The Boodle Build documentation is a separate AI Doc artifact submitted alongside the Position Paper.</p>

